Barack Obama will be the fourth US President to receive the Nobel Peace Prize
U.S. President Barack Obama will fly to Oslo in Norway to spend 26 hours there and be the fourth U.S. president in history to receive the Nobel Peace Prize.
The diploma, medal and $1.4 million cheque will be awarded to him, among other things, for his exceptional efforts to strengthen global diplomacy and collaboration between nations.
The head of the White House and his wife Michelle will land in the Norwegian metropolis in the morning and have a busy program.
He will first visit the Nobel Institute, where he will meet for the first time with the five members of the Committee who chose him in October from among 172 people and 33 organizations.
The presidential couple's schedule then schedules an interview with Norwegian King Harald V and Queen Sonja.
The visit will take place in the afternoon at a solemn ceremony where Obama will receive the prestigious award.
He will be the fourth President of the United States to receive it, but only the third to be awarded the award in the Committee itself.
The White House informed in advance that Obama would talk about the war in Afghanistan at the award.
The president does not want to avoid this issue because he is aware that he is receiving this award by being a president who is waging a war in two countries at the moment.
He strengthened the war effort a few days ago by sending additional units to Afghanistan, which none of his critics will forget to emphasize.
At the ceremony, Obama will also receive a gold medal, a diploma and a cheque of ten million Swedish krones (about 1.1 million euros).
He intends to donate it to charities, but has not yet decided concretely which ones.
His charged program will then take him and his wife to a banquet including, in addition to the king and queen of Norway, the head of government and 250 other guests.
Obama was quite reluctant at this price at first.
He mentioned, for example, having the feeling that he does not deserve it fully.
He also repeated several times that it is not a prize for himself alone, but for all who defend the same values as him.
As soon as he announced, he said it would be a "invitation to act."
