The United Nations Group has draft plans for emissions reduction
The UN-sponsored climate conference -- so far characterized by disorganized assignments and mutual recrimination -- returned to the flames of the ramp on Friday, as a result of the publication of a document highlighting the ambitious reductions in greenhouse gases over the next 40 years, with industrialized nations supporting most of the burden in the coming times.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, highlighted the remaining obstacles, as much as it illuminated the way to go.
But it has been seen as an important step forward in time-lacking negotiations, with more than 100 leaders from around the world arriving next week in Copenhagen.
Drafted by a special UN working group, the text does not say how much rich countries would give to the poor to support global warming, both in the long run and in the long run.
And it offers a wide range of options for key issues, including how developed economies and new emerging economies could decrease their carbon production and what would be the upper limit of the global temperature rise that officials would be willing to tolerate.
It gives great flexibility to the process, said John Coequyt, Sierra Club Washington Representative.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who wrote six pages of the document, studied a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the UN Executive Secretary-General on Climate Change, Yvo de Boer, described as being "the full picture".
It shows the guidelines for a possible agreement in which industrial nations would collectively reduce their emissions by 2020, 25 to 45 percent from 1990 levels, while major developing countries, during the same period, would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 percent.
Together, countries would reduce emissions by 50 to 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union has also relaunched negotiations on Friday, promising to provide $3.6 billion a year for the next three years to help poorest countries adapt to the impact of climate change -- to support floods and drought or to prevent deforestation.
However, on Friday, the same verbal altercations have occurred, which have dominated the negotiations since last week.
Todd Stern, U.S. Climate Negotiation Representative, rejected any discussion requiring greenhouse gas reduction by industrialized countries, compared to voluntary efforts by major emerging economies, if they were not funded by developed countries.
This change is a signal that the Obama administration is becoming harder to China than the Bush administration was two years ago.
The United States will not sign an agreement without the efforts and actions of major developing countries, Stern said he also regretted that the text did not insist enough to ensure that the reductions could be verified by external observers.
Stern made his comments an hour after Chinese Deputy Foreign Minister He Yafei declared that the U.S. chief negotiator either lacked "good sense" or was "extremely irresponsible" for saying earlier this week that the U.S. would not financially help China to fight global warming.
With future economic trajectories of the major world powers at stake, defects have emerged both within the Third World and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current battle is more about rescuing individual economies than about rescuing the planet, with China and the United States arguing about their respective obligations as the poorer nations insist that the two dozen most influential countries ignore the scientific imperatives to act more courageously.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said it was no surprise that major powers were struggling to find out who should suffer the costs of decreasing greenhouse gases, even though vulnerable countries had become more aggressive in their attempts to make major issuers responsible for their actions.
It is really a game in which a new economic hegemony is developed, said Ulate, who is also climate advisor for Mexico and Central America for Conservation International.
Some of these countries, more vulnerable to the impact of climate change, said they would continue to put pressure for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although most key participants say the negotiations will lead to a minimum, political agreement.
The Alliance of Small Island States, which brings together 43 members, has drafted a 24-page treaty proposal, early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, head of the European Commission’s climate unity, said the action of small island states has “put political pressure on the entire political process,” in part because they are now unified and calling on emerging economies such as China and India to act.
The debates became an urgent issue, as delegates focused on the fact that they had to solve most of the problems pending before the heads of governments reached an agreement.
High-level officials such as the Indian Minister of the Environment, Jairam Ramesh and the Chinese Deputy Minister dropped out of their plane and rushed into the Bella Center building to attend closed-door meetings and briefings, in order to be able to make complaints that will be considered over the next week.
The true image of the gathering—in which 13,000 people come in and out of the Palais des Congrès every day—guitar player activists perform night shows mocking countries that they think are betraying each other and proposals are written and distributed on paper rather than by email—is a real challenge.
The intensity is only growing: almost all major ministers are here and no later than Wednesday, 60 heads of government will be in Copenhagen.
We are entering the courtyard of the great, said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, Vice President for Global Policy of Conservation International.
The heavy cars are coming.
