The panel remained nearly 300 years in Rome in the famous collection of the Borghese family, then appeared successively with French actress Cécile Sorel, who had made it an element of her bathtub in her Parisian private hotel, and with Paul Reynaud, minister under the Third Republic in France and briefly chairman of the Council before the accession to power of Marshal Pétain.
It remained a shadow area of about fifty years.
By searching the database of the Louvre Museum, Florent Heintz discovered that this panel was part of a "succession Emile Zola" opened in 1903, a year after the death of the author of "Thérèse Raquin" and the fresco of the "Rougon-Macquart".
