Managing revolution or an end to economic intelligence?
If nothing changes in the governance of large French companies, our struggle for the development of economic intelligence will have been in vain...
For more than a decade, the attitude of the management of large companies towards their employees, reminds the position of companies towards consumers before the marketing revolution: it is about making employees adhere to "values" determined from above as it used to be, to impose on consumers products thought by factory technicians.
By putting the customer at the heart of the company, the marketing revolution has put market conquest strategies to the place... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products disconnected from the factors of customer preferences comes back regularly!
Employee demobilization can lead to deadly demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are only the part of a much more general phenomenon that affects the executives in particular.
This demobilization seriously jeopardizes the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, including R&D and, moreover, economic intelligence.
Indeed, the IE "demands from all stakeholders (...) a proactive approach and a forward-looking vision"; it requires employees to make a commitment that authoritarian management revenues totally contradict.
That is why we call for a management revolution that would be to put employees at the center of business concerns as well as the customer.
The relative usefulness of internal opinion surveys
Will internal opinion surveys – such as the questionnaire submitted by Orange to its employees – incite this revolution in management practices?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
- Firstly because I was able to see that, in the face of a new situation, any structure eventually, after many detours, comes to do priority... what it has always done!
Then, because authoritarianism – one of the pathologies of power – grows proportionally to the importance of its own failures.
Finally, because most leaders have a simplistic view of human behaviour.
They come from major engineering schools and have a mechanistic interpretation of psychology.
They adopt, by intellectual comfort, the old behaviorist theory, recently reactivated by the U.S. "neurosciences" and widely disseminated, without their knowledge, by the institutes of study and the media.
Thus, by suggesting that it is possible to manage the "levards" (sic) of executive engagement, a recent survey by Ipsos published in Le Figaro.fr supports leaders in a posture of mechanistic governance, inadapted to today's world.
Identifying and measuring mobilization factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern enterprises presupposes adopting a finalistic view of human behavior.
It consists of integrating, in any reasoning or practice of governance, a fundamental finding: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it appears clearly as a means of realizing part of their dreams, their ambitions, their projects.
Currently, only the studies derived from the Onctional Motive Analysis adopt this conception of employee motivations.
These studies have shown that they judge their company based on a predetermined doxa that allows them, through their perceived image of the company, to assess what it offers them to realize their life projects.
Through the identification and measurement of these mobilization factors, business leaders can monitor, predict and anticipate their "social performance" and put their human resources management "on the spot".
They thus create a ground for the concerted development of robust and effective economic intelligence.
