The Cradle of the Dinosaurs
The Tawa hallae resembled other carnivorous dinosaurs: this biped was about 2 meters long for 1.50 meters tall, its back limbs were powerful, its skull was elongated with sharp and curved teeth, its short arms ended with sickle claws, and it had a long tail.
If this species had lived a few million years later, it would have had nothing exceptional.
But, as Sertling Nesbitt from the University of Texas in Austin and his colleagues in Thursday's Science magazine reports, the Tawa hallae is one of the first dinosaurs with these morphological characteristics.
This animal lived 215 million years ago in New Mexico, which at the time was part of the emerging lands of the supercontinent, the Pangea, and was located towards the equator.
Sertling Nesbitt says the discovery of the Tawa lights up the evolution of the first dinosaurs on a new day.
Indeed, it informs us about the kinship links, the distribution and the characteristics of the latter.
It was in 2006 that Sertling Nesbitt undertook excavations with other paleontologists at the Gohst Ranch site in northern New Mexico.
Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History and a member of the excavation team tells that sometimes they could find a dozen bones in a day, which is absolutely unique for a sedimentary layer dating from the Trias.
Scientists quickly realized that some of these bones belonged to a new species.
The excavations updated the remains of five specimens.
A discovery that confirms the theories regarding the early evolution of dinosaurs.
Researchers named it Tawa after the word of the Hopi Indians for the god of the sun.
For Sterling Nesbitt, this is a quite exceptional discovery: Dinosaur fossils from the Trias are extremely rare and limited to a few incomplete bone fragments.
Not all experts in paleontology share this enthusiasm.
For example, Martin Sander of the University of Bonn does not find this discovery to be particularly spectacular, but he states that it can confirm certain theories regarding the early evolution of dinosaurs.
According to the current state of knowledge, dinosaurs appeared on Earth about 230 million years ago.
Most of the oldest fossils, however, are fragmented and incomplete, making it very difficult to classify the first dinosaurs.
Experts wonder, among other things, when the saurians were divided into three major evolutionary groups: the theropodes (carnivores) which include the tyrannosaurus and the velociraptor later appeared and from which descend the birds, the sauropodes, quad-footed at the long neck, and those related to them and the herbivores which are part of the ornithisch.
According to the studies of S. Nesbitt and his colleagues, the Tawa is one of the first theropodes.
This species presents an interesting report of both primitive and developed characteristics, says S. Nesbitt.
The researchers found clues that suggest that the Tawa hallae possessed small airbags in its bones at the level of the skull, just like the birds that are the descendants of the theropodes.
These small air pockets make it easier for birds to breathe compared to mammals.
It appears that in the Tawa hallae, the vertebrae were also partially filled with air.
According to Randall Irmis, the Tawa is one of the oldest theropodes with small airbags in its bones.
Since the relative lineage of the huge sauropodes also possessed airbags and a light frame, it may be thought that their common ancestor already had this beneficial innovation.
Three successive waves of migration to North America.
As the most primitive dinosaurs known lived in South America, researchers concluded that the saurians had appeared there.
Therefore, the three major lines of evolution divided and spread from South America to the rest of the world, i.e. all the emerging lands that formed the supercontinent Pangea.
This seems to be confirmed by the fact that the team of paleontologists also discovered the remains of two other theropodes that are not particularly related to it.
The three species cannot descend from a common ancestor that would have migrated, the researchers advance.
Alan Turner of the New York Museum of Natural History and co-author of Science Studies magazine says there would have been at least three waves of migration to North America.
Of course, there are some contradictions.
Martin Sander, a paleontologist in Bonn, says there is an even older species, the Silesaur, who lived in today's Poland and belongs to a group related to dinosaurs.
According to him, this could give an erroneous view because there are a large number of dinosaur fossils in South America that have been preserved while virtually none are found on other continents.
On the other hand, how dinosaurs managed to become the dominant tetrapods of the secondary era while they came from a relatively rare collateral line of the reptile branch, still remains a mystery today.
At the time of the Trias, dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, such as with the ancestors of current crocodiles and with many other saurians.
Towards the end of the Trias the dinosaurs spread across the planet thus encouraging the development of many new species while others, which were related to them, disappeared between the Trias and the Jurassic.
Such success, however, is not eternal.
To explain this transformation, Martin Sander sees two hypotheses.
There may have been a massive extinction that dinosaurs survived randomly while other reptiles would have disappeared.
Or then, the dinosaurs were better suited and thus they were able to eliminate competition on the ground.
In any case, such success is not eternal.
150 million years later, the fall of a favorite meteorite for the flourishing of a group of animals that had also developed during the Trias and that since then was in the shadow: they were mammals.
