The SPD and the Left (Left) parties are asking the chancellor for explanations.
Hamburg/Berlin - After reviewing the latest information on the Kunduz airstrike, the opposition accused Defence Minister Karl-Theodor zu Guttenberg (CSU) of deliberately concealing certain facts.
The Minister intentionally "formulated a falsehood" about the deadly strike of two tankers last September, Greens' parliamentary group leader Jürgen Trittin said Saturday during the news broadcast of the ARD channel "Tagesschau" (the 8 pm newspaper).
Clearly, that means he lied.
The order to kill was given in total disregard of the rules of the International Security Assistance Force in Afghanistan (ISAF).
This is, in substance, the content of the NATO report, which was read by Mr Guttenberg, Trittin said.
Last Friday, according to new media revelations, the goal of the strike was in reality not to destroy the stolen trucks, but to eliminate two important Taliban leaders.
According to the NATO investigation report, 142 people were killed or injured in the U.S. airstrike that was launched at the request of German Colonel Goerg Klein, Military Commander of Kunduz.
The Greens, the SPD and the Left asked Saturday Chancellor Angela Merkel (CDU) to proceed as soon as possible before the federal parliament and reveal what Guttenberg really knew about the incident.
Jürgen Trittin and his colleague from the Green Party, Renate Künast, are of the view that Angela Merkel should make it clear whether the targeted massacre strategy is part of the Afghan policy of the Federal Government and whether the Chancellery, the military and the intelligence services have approved this new strategy.
The Government spokesman strongly rejected these criticisms.
The chancellory has in no way influenced the army's interventions in Afghanistan, he said.
On Saturday, there were increasing voices to express doubtful reasons for the removal of Inspector General Wolfgang Schneiderhan and Secretary of State Peter Wichert, as presented by the Ministry.
According to the newspaper SPIEGEL, the information they had provided to Guttenberg about the attack on tankers was both accurate and complete.
Officially, they would have concealed the existence of the NATO report and concealed some embarrassing details from the Minister.
In the context of the two senior officials, however, it is suggested that they have informed the Ministry of Defence of the existence of several reports, including a two-page Colonel Klein document and a military police report.
The Frankfurter Allgemeiner Sonntagszeitung reports that Wichert had meanwhile asked in a letter for clarification of the facts.
So far, he has not obtained an answer.
On Saturday, the Ministry did not wish to comment on these accusations and referred to the Federal Parliament’s investigative committee that was to be set up on Wednesday to bring light on the facts in question.
The worlds of the dream
Some see, all awake, images and hear voices that no one else sees or hears.
It is not only in psychic patients, or under the effect of drugs, that the boundaries between imagination and reality are confused.
As long as these phenomena manifest during sleep, everything is fine.
When we lie down in our dark rooms, we can give ourselves unhindered to the craziest dreams and fantasies.
However, anyone who, awake, experiences a dream state, hears and sees things that others do not perceive, quickly has the reputation in our Western world of being mad or drugged, or at least of being an original.
Such images and voices appear not only in psychic patients or under the effect of drugs.
It is our imagination that is in question: it is the same neural activity that allows us to design houses, paint paintings or write novels, but which sometimes incites the boundaries between dream, madness and reality to merge.
A state of conscious awakening, taking the form of a dream, can present itself in the most diverse forms, in the best of cases this is called visions, in the worst of madness.
But even though the trigger and effect differ, the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the drug experiments of the New Age prophet Carlos Castaneda, the secondary states of shamans, psychoses and hallucinations are attributable to very similar processes.
There are hallucinations or delusions when the balance, neurotransmitting substances in the brain - first of all dopamine, norepinephrine, serotonin and achetylcholine - breaks and the interaction between the different parts of the brain is disrupted.
Complex hallucinations and delusional thoughts manifest very often during schizophrenic psychosis.
The terrestrial force of attraction no longer has power over the person.
Since ancient times, philosophers and physicians have always looked at the relationship between madness and dream.
For Aristotle, hallucinations were a form of dream-awakening; Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, saw in 1861 "a great resemblance between madness and dream", for Sigmund Freud, the dream was even "a psychosis with all the irregularities, imaginations, delusions and sensory illusions that compose it."
It's in autumn 2001 when Henning T turns into a comic book character.
His body is in two dimensions with crisp colors.
The earthly attraction no longer has power over it, it flies down the ceiling.
He's feeling a blow.
Behind him winged creatures of devil, crimping, his mouth bleeding, showing his teeth.
They pursue him, kick him with heavy flaming boots, throw him against the walls, he feels pain throughout the body.
Tonituring, evil, screaming voices coming out of the walls and radio.
He can no longer stand those voices that insult and humiliate him.
Henning T. pulls out two cables from his stereo chain, in fact a loop and attaches it to a hook attached to the ceiling.
It climbs on a baffle and runs the loop around the neck.
He's jumping.
The loop is detached.
Let it be a lesson for you, shout the voices in a choir to rip off his tympan, "Go to a clinic and get healed!"
Today, Henning T. is 40 years old, he has experienced six acute psychoses, the last is two years old, the first is nearly 20 years old.
It was triggered by LSD.
Diagnosis: schizo-affective psychosis, paranoid, in addition he is maniac-depressive, he takes medications for depression, mania, schizophrenia.
He learned to live with his illness, he has been married for three years.
During psychosis I experienced terrible fears and deep despair.
Illusions are a cruel reality.
Approximately one percent of the population suffers from schizophrenia at least once in their lifetime; in psychiatric clinics it is the most common disease after depression.
In a crisis of schizophrenia, those affected can no longer distinguish between the inner world and the outer world, they find themselves in a state of hyper excitement, which can cause them to suffer from hallucinations, megalomania, relationship madness or persecution.
It is very common to hear voices – voices that command, comment or dialogue.
Optical hallucinations are not rare either.
The person concerned can no longer distinguish between the important and the insignificant, the brain can no longer filter the disruptive signals, the conscious is drowned under sensations.
Like the dream, psychosis opens the locks to a tide of ideas and fantasies from the deeper layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is centered on the subject, according to Professor Thomas Fuchs, head of the Department of Psychiatry at the CHU in Heidelberg (Allgemeine Psychiatrie im Universitätsklinikum).
The schizophrenic is in the middle of the situation, all with a meaning centered on it.
At the same time, he finds himself in a passive role, he is like in a dream, overcome by events and cannot act actively on them.
This is why schizophrenics often feel threatened, controlled, and manipulated.
In general, they do not have the possibility to adjust reality, illusions are a cruel reality, waking up is excluded.
Experience a hallucination once in your life.
Unlike the dream, according to Fuchs, “the sensory and spatial structure of reality that is perceived during psychosis, is fundamentally preserved.”
Delirant thoughts and hallucinations are based on reality, the alienation of the living takes place in a real setting.
Why our brain makes these kinds of cabriolets, is still a mystery for researchers.
Exceptional situations can cause everyone to lose momentarily the perception of reality, according to Fuchs.
But only a small number of people will develop psychosis.
There appears to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but studies on twins have shown that genes are not the only determinants.
The researchers assume that those affected have minor brain injury.
Neural maturation of the brain is assumed to be disrupted at an early stage of development, for example by a viral infection of the mother during pregnancy, Fuchs explains.
But what remains unexplained is how the neuronal system anomaly occurs and also the fact that it does not manifest for many years.
Environmental factors also play a role – stress or a traumatic experience can be a trigger of psychosis, if there is a predisposition.
Similarly, hallucinogenic drugs can trigger psychoses because they act on neurotransmitters.
When our brain warms.
What is crazy, says psychology professor Erich Kasten of Lübeck, is that psychotics suffer from their hallucinations and take expensive drugs to get rid of them while others buy very expensive drugs to get them.
The pleasant or unpleasant perception of illusions is often just a question of perspective.
For ten years, Kasten has gathered reports on hallucinations and phenomena of illusory images: last year he published his results in a book entitled "The unreal world in our heads".
Hallucinations are well part of the concomitant phenomena typical of psychoses but also an impressive number of many other pathologies.
These include mental disorders such as borderline or depression but also migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis, Alzheimer's disease or cranial trauma.
It is surprising to note that in certain conditions even the brains of healthy people are subject to hallucinations.
Hallucinations, according to Kasten, consist of fragments of memories that are normally inhibited.
They take shape when areas of the brain that process sensory perceptions are hyperactive or not sufficiently retained; when our brain warms up, but also when there is no stimulation.
Drugs can trigger this condition just like brain injury or psychosis.
But also the lack of stimulus, stress, grief of love or other exceptional mental states.
In recent studies, one-third of the participants acknowledged having experienced a hallucination at least once in their lifetime.
