That’s why Kasten advises his patients to cherish hallucinations as a particular talent.
There is only one step between dream and hallucination.
In our world too focused on consciousness, we unfortunately quickly tend to take imaginary experiments for pathologies, according to Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor at Heidelberg and chief doctor of the clinic of psychiatry and psychotherapy at the Florence Nightingale Hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a serious, painful illness but also contains something positive, creative - madness is a work of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard studied the so-called oniroid form of experience, a particular form of the change in consciousness awakened by the dream.
Oniroid experiences are very complex semi-dreams that are perceived as real by the one who lives them and that he cannot differentiate from the dream even when he is awake.
Oniroid consciousness manifests itself during trauma or in situations of extreme pathologies as for patients with polyradiculopathy who are fully aware, experience motor paralysis.
According to Schmidt-Degenhard, when a human being is threatened by a loss of self and the world, due to a total and lasting inability to move, he replaces this real situation that affects his life, by his own imaginary world that is dissociated from reality.
It is a state of mental boundary between dream and hallucination.
Since it is not possible to overcome the situation in reality, a world change is taking place but the real situation is represented in the imagination.
In fact, it is an intense form of means and interpretation, in an intolerable situation in itself, an organizational capacity which is given to us men not to sink into the nothingness of loss of consciousness.
Everything is real even later in memories.
The Zurichian Peter Cornelius Classen, an art historian, also describes his oniroid experiences in his book "Change of Heart" as an action to safeguard the soul.
He is 49 years old, at the time his conscious departs for a journey of several days after the operation of a heart valve followed by a transplant; during this time, his body is doomed to remain immobile in reanimation.
Claussen plunges into a world that he has created, visiting foreign places, traveling in time. He sees himself as an old man lying in a railway sanatorium, a robot at his bedside watching over his health.
He lived in the Middle Ages among nobles who made blood-based narcotics.
He is kidnapped by a Greek motorcyclist who takes him to his country, he surfs with his hospital bed in the Alps and meets a Korean mafia.
It completely absorbs into this imaginary world, everything is real even later in his memories.
According to Claussen, these inner journeys are fundamentally different from any dream.
The dream is a completely different state, he writes describing what he has experienced.
Unlike dreams, memories from mental journeys are of extreme clarity and very detailed even years later.
It can even be said that they are much more distinct and more intense than the real experience.
The intensity of this experience bursts the horizon of our other daily experiences, according to psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
Ultimately, oniroid delusions, psychoses, hallucinations and psychedelic experiences show us how fragile our inner representations of external reality are even in a standby state.
Any change in the state of consciousness, the psychologist Kasten summarizes, "can cause a distortion of what we call reality."
An experience that can also be quite rewarding.
