Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women from younger generations who want to be mothers.
This is revealed by the study "Fertility and professional career of women in Spain", conducted by the CSIC in collaboration with the Instituto de la Mujer.
The survey of 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 leaves no doubt: 75% of working mothers saw their careers limited because of maternity.
The study indicates that there are many differences in the beginning of couple life and the number of children, whether or not the woman works and the type of employment occupied.
Those who do not have activity outside the home, work part-time, or have an unstable job, get married earlier, have their first pregnancy earlier, and have more children.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, push back entry into couple life and first pregnancy, and have fewer children.
Women between the ages of 35 and 49 with fixed work have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after settling in a couple. This figure rises to 4.1 for women working in the public sector. "These data show that women with stable work needed more time in their lives to obtain it, which led them to push back union and the arrival of children.
In addition, the type of employment exercised largely influences maternity, but less the start date of common life,” explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that deepens the gap in the age of marriage of women and their first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of training, the more they get married and have their first child late.
The difference also remains among women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49-year-old group, those who completed elementary and higher studies were mothers for the first time at an average of 25.1 and 32.1 years respectively.
“Another discretion also appears among women, depending on their level of study.
While those who have completed elementary studies marry and have their first child before finding a stable job, those who have completed middle or higher education reverse this program and give priority to obtaining a stable job as a prerequisite for marriage and the arrival of a child,” said Delgado.
