Emergency braking assistance is now mandatory
As it happened with the ABS brake anti-lock system and as it will happen with the ESP stability control, emergency braking assistance systems will be a mandatory element on European cars.
They are already mandatory for newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for the rest of the vehicles a lack period was set until the end of February 2011.
The measure, imposed by the European Union, aims to strengthen the protection of pedestrians, although, through its mode of action, it can also help to avoid many back shocks.
The emergency braking assistant acts by increasing the pressure on the brakes in the event of an emergency detected by the system thanks to the kick given by the driver.
But the latter does not always keep the pressure until the end.
According to a study conducted by Bosch car components manufacturer, one-third of the drivers involved in an accident had not been able to press the brake before the collision, and half of them had not taken full advantage of its strength.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The intervention of the aid, in revenge, demands the maximum of the brake system, reducing the distance the car needs to stop.
According to an EU study, if all cars were equipped with such elements, up to 1,100 fatal accidents in which pedestrians are involved could be avoided each year.
This reduction would be even greater with the popularization of the so-called intelligent emergency braking systems: one in four disasters with injuries is estimated to be avoided.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that, through a radar or camera, detects obstacles and prevents the driver, in addition to acting slightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, he/she assists him/her by increasing the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
If it does not react, and although the collision is inevitable, the device exerts maximum effort on the brakes to minimize damage.
