New tools for car expertise
In these days of bad weather and accidents, car garages are not the only winners.
Every day, thousands of cars who have suffered a disaster are brought back to a garage, where an expert has to assess the damage suffered and the cost of repair.
Each disaster is different, and the calculation of the cost of pieces and labor time can be a long and complex work.
Hand calculating the cost of a repair between 20,000 and 30,000 euros, including parts and workforce can take two or three hours.
On the other hand, with the support of the latest IT tools, it would be a matter of minutes.
This is why nearly 100% of experts use these types of systems.
Service and solutions providers for claim assessment and maintenance are dedicated to collecting the information provided by manufacturers, and then processing it and offering it to their customers as a useful tool.
In Spain, Audatex, of the North American group Solera, is the leading company; 80% of the estimates are made with its products.
Other companies competing in the field of evaluation tools and the development of information on the sector are GtMotive and Eurotax.
Working with the data provided by manufacturers is far from simple.
According to Eduardo Velázquez, sales director of Audatex, the company in Spain with 63 manufacturers and importers, and each of them provides them with information in a different format.
In addition, the amount of data to be processed is increasing, so that over the last five years more versions, variants and engines have been launched than in the previous fifteen years.
When a new car comes into the market, these companies get to work.
This is a very hard work, because you have to catalogue each of the thousand parts of the vehicle and register its price.
In addition, a “smart” graphical image of each model can be created to click on the different parts of a passenger car.
If this is a massively sold model, the work can be ready in a week if the process progresses very quickly.
If it is a low-selling car, it can take three or four months. Currently, Audatex has comprehensive information on 99.2% of cars sold in Spain.
Among the most exclusive models, they have information about Porsches, for example, but not Ferrari or Lamborghini.
For vehicles in circulation, the figure exceeds 99%.
To carry out the documentation and database development work, Audatex has eight centres worldwide (in Spain, France, Germany, the United States, Brazil, Mexico, China and Japan), each of which specializes in certain brands.
The national headquarters is located in Alcobendas (Madrid).
There, more than one hundred technicians (usually mechanical experts) work simultaneously on three computer screens.
Audatex invests 90 million dollars each year to develop these databases.
Every month, 2.5 million data is recorded, and customers receive updates every two days.
The development of this enormous flow of information allows these companies to give them different uses and offer various products.
The most common application relates to repair and maintenance, but depending on the country, there are also tools for managing broken parts or to calculate the venal or residual value of a car.
The only company that has a guide that informs about the value of used cars in Spain is Eurotax.
Audatex does not offer it in our country, but it does it in the United States.
In view of the products offered by Audatex, it is easy to get an idea of the type of support it can provide to industry professionals.
This company offers ten different tools, the flagship product being AudaPlus, the standard disaster assessment solution for experts.
There are cars, motorcycles, light and heavy industrial vehicles.
In addition to the cost of parts, it takes into account the repair times estimated by the manufacturer or paint scales.
This tool is purchased according to its use, for each estimate.
The highest cost is 5.75 euros, for customers who use it little, a maximum of ten times a month.
Then each insurance company, which carries out thousands of expertise, negotiates its price with Audatex.
Other products, such as AudaVIN, allow the full identification of a vehicle and the equipment with which it came out of the assembly line, only thanks to its chassis number.
AudaGlass focuses on vehicle lenses, and AudaSubastas is an open-to-professional server on the Internet that bids on vehicles declared wrecked.
Its statistical service is very useful in identifying trends, performing geo-demographic analysis or knowing common problems by brand or model.
It is possible to study, for example, how many models of a particular brand went to the garage for a breakdown or how many suffered serious disasters for a given period of time.
Gt Motive is the only Spanish company dedicated to the development of this type of tools.
It markets, among other things, Gt Estimate, which is also intended for experts and provides digital images, as well as access to the official parts, prices and time of the manufacturer.
Gt Motive is a company of the Einsa Group, founded in 1971, as a provider of services and solutions for the assessment of claims, failures or car maintenance.
The GT Assessment Guide is a historic reference product on the market.
The company works with 24,000 users in garages, 3,100 experts and 53 insurance companies.
Its turnover has increased at a rate of 20% per year over the past three years, with a turnover of €10.8 million in 2008.
At the beginning of last year, it began its internationalization process, with the establishment of an office in Paris.
Audatex was born in Germany in 1966 and settled in Spain in 1979.
According to the company's sources, 62% of its turnover is in Europe and the rest of the world, and the remaining 38% in North and South America. It works with 900 insurance companies and 33,000 garages, of which 3,000 are located in Spain.
